<div id="review_297661229" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/297661229" />
    <a title="Tuck" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/565487-tuck"><img alt="Tuck" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1461699620p2/565487.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/297661229?book_show_action=true">Mar 20, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tuck" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tuck" href="/user/show/565487-tuck">Tuck</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer297661229" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6963573665473151887">a classic modern indian novel of a young man starting his career in the IAS indian admin service. many funny and cynical jokings of country folk and bureaucrats, our protag august is in training in madna, a hot, dusty, very out-of-the-way town where he learns the ropes of running the biggest free country in the world. cynical in that his heart really isn&apos;t in it and bides his time smoking doobies and jacking off, while drinking and cadging suppers off his bosses and friends. after this stellar s</span>
  <span id="freeText6963573665473151887" style="display:none">a classic modern indian novel of a young man starting his career in the IAS indian admin service. many funny and cynical jokings of country folk and bureaucrats, our protag august is in training in madna, a hot, dusty, very out-of-the-way town where he learns the ropes of running the biggest free country in the world. cynical in that his heart really isn't in it and bides his time smoking doobies and jacking off, while drinking and cadging suppers off his bosses and friends. after this stellar start he thinks he will just quit, take a lousy job in new dehli and hopefully hang out on his roof, read books, smoke doobies, jack off etc etc. but he is talked out of this "disastrous" career move by uncle, dad, friend, and himself and goes back to training. he gets a couple month stint WAY out in the boonies and seems to take an interest in the tribals and their water woes, and their dignity? the reader is pulling for august, really, but in the end....he just can't face a lifetime of bureaucracy and laziness, so comes to the brilliant plan of dropping out and, what?, hanging out on the roof, reading books, smoking....<br />in a sort of inside joke, the author IS a bureaucrat/technocrat and writes novels "on the side". wonderful book and i want to read more upamanyu chatterjee, so much insight into religion, economics, rural/urban attitudes, food, travel (foreign and domestic), humor, love, sex, health. just chock full of accessible inside dope on india.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6963573665473151887" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


